<ComingSoonRoomLayout
  room="court"
  title="Court Room"
  subtitle="Case files, court decisions, legal opinions."
  sourceId="coming-soon-court"
>
  <p>
    The Court Room will hold the doctrinal record: the decisions that built
    fiduciary law and the cases that have applied it to school-trust
    questions across the fifty states. Cardozo's 1928 opinion in
    <em>Meinhard v. Salmon</em>, with its "punctilio of an honor the most
    sensitive," sits at the front of the docket — it's the standard every
    school-trust trustee is measured against. Behind it, the trust-corpus
    cases of the 1880s; <em>Lassen v. Arizona</em>; the beneficiary-standing
    decisions; the modern accounting-fraud rulings.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why this room matters.</strong> Doctrine is the second pillar of
    the school-trust experiment, after the lands themselves. Without it the
    trustees are unbound; with it they answer to a standard that has held
    for a century and counting. A reader who wants to understand what
    fiduciary duty <em>means</em> in school-trust context — and why states
    that ignore it can be called to account — should read here.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Doctrine on Trial.</strong> A recurring section will track the
    questions currently being argued about across the country — the
    standing tests, the corpus-irreducibility tests, the trustee-officer
    immunity tests — so a reader can see which way the law is moving and
    where the frontier sits.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Being planned.</strong> <em>Meinhard</em> goes up first.
  </p>
</ComingSoonRoomLayout>
